Painful tic convulsif caused by a contralateral vertebral artery.
 The case of trigeminal neuralgia and ipsilateral hemifacial spasm--painful tic convulsif--is presented.
 Microsurgical exploration revealed compression of the fifth and seventh cranial nerves by a tortuous contralateral vertebral artery.
 Neurovascular decompression of the roots entry/exit zone completely relieved preoperative facial pain and spasm.
